th outside of marriage, and prostitution. Professor Lévesque concludes, "They were deviant, but only in relation to a norm upheld to stave off a modernism that threatened to swallow up a Quebec based on long-established social and sexual roles."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 0aMotherhoodzQuébec (Province)xHistoryy20th century. 0aMotherhoodzQuébec (Province)xHistoryy20th century. 0aProstitutionzQuébec (Province)xHistoryy20th century. 0aProstitutionzQuébec (Province)xHistoryy20th century. 0aWomenxSexual behaviorzQuébec (Province)xHistoryy20th century. 0aWomenxSexual behaviorzQuébec (Province)xHistoryy20th century. 0aWomenzQuébec (Province)xConduct of lifexHistoryy20th century. 0aWomenzQuébec (Province)xConduct of lifexHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Canada / Post-Confederation (1867-).2bisacsh1 aKlein, Yvonne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144262784040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442627840423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781442627840/original  a978-3-11-049094-7  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999c1933d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK